My return visit to Gary Danko was exceptional, which is what you would expect for a Michelin rated restaurant and one of the best places in SF. We were a bit late to get to the restaurant and showed up after the last seating but they very nicely welcomed us and served the full multi-course meal. All of the food was 5 stars and included seared ahi tuna with avocado, risotto with dungeness crab, lobster salad with pistachio mousse, seared sea scallops with sweet pea puree, seared filet of beef with potato gratin, warm Louisiana butter cake with apples, and baked chocolate souffle.

Wow where to start.... I have been dining at Gary Danko many times, however since moving to New York It has been some time so on a recent trip to San Francisco my grandmother (who frequents) invited my sister and I for dinner on Friday May 25th. Since this was a last min outing we did not have reservations so we lined up early for a seat at the bar (where we have dined before on a whim visits and greatly enjoyed). Our meal was exceptional as always however It pains me to write this review as this is one of my favorite SF restaurants, but as a Michelin star restaurant the treatment we received needs to be shared with others. The treatment we received from Tommy the bartender and Brian the "manager" was DEPLORABLE, DEGRADING, RACIST AND OFFENSIVE! After dinner we split a chocolate souffle and were given the complimentary sweets. However, after our meal we were all too full to eat it. My grandmother kindly asked Tommy to pack them for us and that's when things went south. He replied "no we only give one per household" and that's when I calmly replied stating that ALL THE TIMES I've been there (5+ times) vie always received my own sweets box along with the breakfast cake. I also kindly mentioned to him that I understand that perhaps rules changed, however I was not going to the same household as my sister and grandmother and was staying in a hotel as I'm visiting from NY and if he could please accommodate as those are my absolute favorite sweets. His reply was condescending and sarcastic "Are you seriously asking me to break the rules" his tone was almost joking so I thought he was displaying some sort of dry humor when I smiled and replied "please". Well that's when he pulled a Houdini act with our check and credit card and in came Brian guns blazing. Brian's introduction consisted of "I hear you guys threatened Tommy you would cause a scene if you didn't get the take home deserts" wow what a welcoming way to treat patrons who are spending upwards of $600 on dinner! And coming from a "manager" at a Michelin restaurant! At this moment I calmly put down my cappuccino and replied "excuse me would you like to tell me who said this when I asked if my sister (a 24-year-old Latina) had said this he said NO, my 74-year-old Caucasian grandmother: NO, Me (28-year-old Latina) NO .... Ok so after exposing him blatantly lying I stated NOBODY THREATENED TO CAUSE A SCENE and I don't appreciate you talking to me in this tone and making FALSE accusations and fabricated stories all I did was kindly ask for an additional box of sweets to enjoy in my hotel room. During this time Tommy enters with the WRONG receipt for us to sign. Ok so not only does Tommy make guests feel awkward when ordering or asking questions, he also fabricates stories against patrons and because he is so wrapped up in "causing a scene" he is incapable of doing his JOB of taking checks to parties. When we mentioned to Brian about the wrong check he once again became irate and talked rudely to us to the point that I got my phone to record his nasty and confrontational attitude towards us. We were 3 women who were simply enjoying each others company, food and asked for a sweet box to go ( the restaurant was not even that packed) I didn't get a chance to even finish my coffee because Brian came around behind us basically cornering us and TOLD US THAT WE NEEDED TO LEAVE OR ELSE HE WAS GOING TO CALL THE POLICE. This experience of overt SEXISM, RACISM, DISCRIMINATION, DEGRADING BEHVIOR was beyond mortifying for me as other patrons saw how we were verbally abused and then physically corralled as he continued to attack us. I left this restaurant in tears! Its 2018 and to experience this in a Michelin restaurant In SF a city that celebrates diversity I am appalled. I hope that Gary or someone in management addresses this issue immediately as after reading other reviews I see it is not the first time he has caused patrons to feel uncomfortable. This behavior is completely unacceptable and I will plan on releasing the video to media outlets so that others do not fall victim of this as we did.

Everything was delicious and the service was immaculate. Restroom fully stocked with fresh hand towels and table reset perfectly between courses

I really debated between 3 and 4 stars. Value for the price ... 3 stars. Overall dining experience ... 4 stars. Experience wins out over value because the meal here was good and memorable. I was in San Francisco for the week and was really debating going to French Laundry. I knew a concierge who might be able to get me a last minute reservation ... but ultimately, I think I am too novice a foodie to drop $350 - $500 per person on a meal. I need a bit more foodie polish before half a grand per person is worth it. However, Danko's $111 for the 5 course tasting or $92 for the 4 course seemed like a reasonable splurge. Normally you need to make reservations at least 2 months in advance (and even then, you are likely to be pushed towards the 5:30 or 9 p.m. slots which are the least desired). The dining room only seats 65 and you can also eat at the bar. First observation ... LOUD! In the side dining room, we were sat right next to the door which meant a partial view of the bar crowd. And being able to hear them. I took one star off for that ... we were one of the first to be seated, yet the host placed us at the worst table. Even in the corners of the room, the sound was much louder than I'd expect from a dimly lit romantic restaurant. One quick note ... please gentlemen, you are not going to a fucking Applebees. At least 25% of the younger male diners in the restaurant were wearing jeans and a polo shirt. I realize that this is the 'do whatever I feel like' generation ... but still ... have some class you idiots. Just because the restaurant is located in the tourist mecca of Fisherman's Wharf doesn't mean you have to dress like you are going to get ice cream at Ghiardeli next door. I really wish Gary Danko would institute a dress policy. If you want to wear jeans ... eat at the bar. If you want to eat in the dining room ... put on a tie and/or jacket. it's not like they wouldn't still fill up. The menu is not your typical chef's tasting menu. You have that option if you want ($111 set menu by the chef.) Or ... if you prefer, you can pick 5 courses for $111, 4 courses for $94, or 3 courses for $75. Here is THE most important tip you will get in any review about Gary Danko ... you are NOT limited to the categories when ordering. On the menu is a list of dishes separated by 'salad, meat, fish, dessert, etc.' If you want to get 5 fish dishes ... or 4 desserts and 1 meat dish ... or 3 appetizers and 2 desserts ... you chose WHICHEVER dishes you want. Don't think you have to order one from each section. This is fairly unique for a tasting menu type of restaurant. I had 4 courses ... Glazed Oysters (Danko's version of French Laundry's Oysters and Pearls) ... it was okay. Juniper Crusted Bison (which, even ordered rare was a bit chewy and hard) ... Filet Minion (the worst dish of the meal ... covered in a way too sweet mix of sugary onions and some kind of mariscapone butter. so sweet I felt like it was a dessert steak) and the Chocolate Souflet with 2 sauces (good ... but you are essentially paying $20 for a dessert if you order one, so it better be good) The carrot soup that came out as an amuse bouche was a complete whiff. It tasted like sweet broth. The food was good ... but I felt that Gary Danko must have a sweet tooth because everything seemed to be overly sweet tasting and sugary. (except the oysters). I would like more savory/salty to balance out the sweetness. Size-wise, your level of fullness will vary based on the dishes you order. The baked lobster consists of 2 or 3 pieces of lobster and a fancy presentation. Order 4 dishes like this and you will leave hungry. If you order 2 or 3 dishes from the meat section, you will leave full. Danko does give you generally more food than you would get on most tasting menus set up like this. Overall, I felt that for the price, the food didn't match up. But the overall experience was good and everyone I came with left happy. So, I would say that the value for the meal was good. $600 for 4 people with liquor is a bargain compared to French Laundry but the quality is not the same. If you break it down, you basically will pay around $20 - $25 per dish depending on how many courses you order. The wine steward was pretty knowledgable. A bit pretentious but in a good way. But do not skip the Madiera ... Gary Danko has one of the largest Madiera selections in the country on the menu. Our waitor was great ... maybe a bit rough for what you'd expect at a top restaurant, but fun and gracious. The staff here really makes the difference. Put aside the '#1 tripadvisor or yelp ' restaurant rankings. Those mean nothing. (several reviews I read on tripadvisor about Gary Danko clearly show that reviewer should stick with Cheesecake Factory recommendations based on their knowledge of fine dining). However, the Michelin stars and James Beard awards don't lie. Gary Danko is worth the hype and you will have a memorable and great meal here.

Then we were immediately greeted with an amuse bouche. It was almost like a carrot soup and was a good way to get our tastebuds excited. Every bit of the evening was truly an experience to remember. We opted for the 3-course dinner for $75 each. Lastly, I opted for the roast maine lobster with potato puree. It was also delicious and completed my night of a seafood-filled meal. I also got a chance to try my bf's lobster risotto. Now that's a good lobster dish! My only wish was there was more to go around!     My return visit to Gary Danko was exceptional, which is what you would expect for a Michelin rated restaurant and one of the best places in SF.  We were a bit late to get to the restaurant and showed up after the last seating but they very nicely welcomed us and served the full multi-course meal.  All of the food was 5 stars and included seared ahi tuna with avocado, risotto with dungeness crab, lobster salad with pistachio mousse, seared sea scallops with sweet pea puree, seared filet of beef with potato gratin, warm Louisiana butter cake with apples, and baked chocolate souffle.

    1000th Review - Yes, I had to wait for a worthy 5 star review and it deservingly was Gary Danko.  I had tried to make a reservation but they were booked for the weekends that I wanted; nonetheless, I get a call on Friday mid-day and bingo, I'm in.  It was a ten o'clock reservation but the restaurant was still packed and the food and service spot on.  Got seated in a quaint corner table a few minutes before the res time and had non-stop top of the line service.  As for the food, here it is:
    + Sweet Corn Soup with Dungeness Crab, Bacon, Red Pepper, Crème Fraîche and Chive Biscuit (1st place, aka best dish of the night, fantastically developed flavor, 5 stars seems too common for this unique dish)
    + Risotto with Lobster, Rock Shrimp, Shimeji Mushrooms, Corn, Roasted Tomatoes and Peas (2nd best dish of the night, deep rich flavor and lots of lobster, just a bit heavy as a starter, i.e. I was almost full after the appetizer - a solid 5 stars)
    + Salad of Heirloom Tomatoes with Burrata, Pesto and Eggplant Chips
    + Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Chanterelle Mushrooms, Corn and Tarragon (tied for 3rd best dish of the night, just good old buttery and succulent lobster, definitely 5 stars and maybe a strong consideration for 2nd best dish)
    + Juniper Crusted Bison with King Trumpet Mushrooms, Glazed Cipollini Onions and Herb Spaetzle (4th best dish of the night, good flavor but bison is not as tender as the filet of course, the spaetzle can be heavy if you eat all of it, a respectable 4.5 stars)
    + Seared Filet of Beef with Yukon Potatoes, Swiss Chard, Tomato-Corn Relish and Basil Butter (tied for 3rd best dish of the night, well cooked filet with good flavor, worthy of 5 stars)
    + Chocolate Praline Parfait with Bourbon Sauce and Salted Caramel Ice Cream (5th best dish of the night, great paline parfait and wonderful ice cream, 4.5 stars)
    + Baked Chocolate Soufflé with Two Sauces (believe it or not, this was the 6th best dish of the night, maybe because it was served last which meant taste buds and stomach were on overload, nonetheless it depends on the expectations you have going in for a souffle, it was very rich and had awesome chocolate flavor, the texture just seemed a bit underbaked, still 4 stars).
    + Tomato gespacio for the chef taster and the bread were good accompaniments.

    Overall, one of the best dining experiences in the country, a 5 star restaurant, and my coveted 1000th review.

    PS - the signed menu from the evening was a perfect finishing touch.

    West Hollywood, CA

    Elite '2020

    Share review

    Embed review

    7/21/2014

    I really debated between 3 and 4 stars.

    Value for the price ... 3 stars.
    Overall dining experience ... 4 stars.
    Experience wins out over value because the meal here was good and memorable.

    I was in San Francisco for the week and was really debating going to French Laundry. I knew a concierge who might be able to get me a last minute reservation ... but ultimately, I think I am too novice a foodie to drop $350 - $500 per person on a meal. I need a bit more foodie polish before half a grand per person is worth it. However, Danko's $111 for the 5 course tasting or $92 for the 4 course seemed like a reasonable splurge. Normally you need to make reservations at least 2 months in advance (and even then, you are likely to be pushed towards the 5:30 or 9 p.m. slots which are the least desired). The dining room only seats 65 and you can also eat at the bar.

    First observation ... LOUD! In the side dining room, we were sat right next to the door which meant a partial view of the bar crowd. And being able to hear them. I took one star off for that ... we were one of the first to be seated, yet the host placed us at the worst table. Even in the corners of the room, the sound was much louder than I'd expect from a dimly lit romantic restaurant.

    One quick note ... please gentlemen, you are not going to a fucking Applebees. At least 25% of the younger male diners in the restaurant were wearing jeans and a polo shirt. I realize that this is the 'do whatever I feel like' generation ... but still ... have some class you idiots. Just because the restaurant is located in the tourist mecca of Fisherman's Wharf doesn't mean you have to dress like you are going to get ice cream at Ghiardeli next door. I really wish Gary Danko would institute a dress policy. If you want to wear jeans ... eat at the bar. If you want to eat in the dining room ... put on a tie and/or jacket. it's not like they wouldn't still fill up.

    The menu is not your typical chef's tasting menu. You have that option if you want ($111 set menu by the chef.) Or ... if you prefer, you can pick 5 courses for $111, 4 courses for $94, or 3 courses for $75.

    Here is THE most important tip you will get in any review about Gary Danko ... you are NOT limited to the categories when ordering. On the menu is a list of dishes separated by 'salad, meat, fish, dessert, etc.' If you want to get 5 fish dishes ... or 4 desserts and 1 meat dish ... or 3 appetizers and 2 desserts ... you chose WHICHEVER dishes you want. Don't think you have to order one from each section. This is fairly unique for a tasting menu type of restaurant.

    I had 4 courses ... Glazed Oysters (Danko's version of French Laundry's Oysters and Pearls) ... it was okay. Juniper Crusted Bison (which, even ordered rare was a bit chewy and hard) ... Filet Minion (the worst dish of the meal ... covered in a way too sweet mix of sugary onions and some kind of mariscapone butter. so sweet I felt like it was a dessert steak) and the Chocolate Souflet with 2 sauces (good ... but you are essentially paying $20 for a dessert if you order one, so it better be good)

    The carrot soup that came out as an amuse bouche was a complete whiff. It tasted like sweet broth. The food was good ... but I felt that Gary Danko must have a sweet tooth because everything seemed to be overly sweet tasting and sugary. (except the oysters). I would like more savory/salty to balance out the sweetness.

    Size-wise, your level of fullness will vary based on the dishes you order. The baked lobster consists of 2 or 3 pieces of lobster and a fancy presentation. Order 4 dishes like this and you will leave hungry. If you order 2 or 3 dishes from the meat section, you will leave full. Danko does give you generally more food than you would get on most tasting menus set up like this.

    Overall, I felt that for the price, the food didn't match up. But the overall experience was good and everyone I came with left happy. So, I would say that the value for the meal was good. $600 for 4 people with liquor is a bargain compared to French Laundry but the quality is not the same. If you break it down, you basically will pay around $20 - $25 per dish depending on how many courses you order.

    The wine steward was pretty knowledgable. A bit pretentious but in a good way. But do not skip the Madiera ... Gary Danko has one of the largest Madiera selections in the country on the menu. Our waitor was great ... maybe a bit rough for what you'd expect at a top restaurant, but fun and gracious. The staff here really makes the difference.

    Put aside the '#1 tripadvisor or yelp ' restaurant rankings. Those mean nothing. (several reviews I read on tripadvisor about Gary Danko clearly show that reviewer should stick with Cheesecake Factory recommendations based on their knowledge of fine dining). However, the Michelin stars and James Beard awards don't lie. Gary Danko is worth the hype and you will have a memorable and great meal here.

    After a much anticipated 2 month reservation, I went to Gary Danko with my husband for our anniversary. Upon walking in I felt instantly upscale. They have extremely large vases with huge flavors that line the walls. I'm talking 5 ft long vases and extravagant flowers. It was great.

    Even though we had gotten a reservation for months, the table we were seated at was the most awkward small one just pushed in between others. The waiter had to pull the table from the wall so I could get in, which made it very uncomfortable because it was pushed all the way back. For a high end place, I was expecting better.

    Now the food. We started with complimentary onion soup. It was tiny to say the least, about 3 spoonfuls. It was good, but nothing to blow my mind. I started with the sweet corn and crab soup while my husband got the ahi tuna. My soup was good, his tuna had way too much seasoning to where it made it sour.

    Then we moved on seafood. I got the salmon medallion which was tasty, followed by the guinea hen. This was my least favorite dish. It came with what looked like another meat. I asked the waiter what it was, but his french accent was so thick I couldn't understand. I felt bad asking for more than two times. We later determined it was guinea hen leg meat. I found the taste to be horrible.

    I saved a good spot for dessert and it was worth it. I got the chocolate soufflé which I would absolutely recommend. It was phenomenal. They serve it in a  coffee mug type bowl and pour chocolate and carmel right into it at the table. Absolutely delicious.

    We also got a complimentary chocolate cake, and little biscuits at the end. They also gave me a banana bread cake to go as a anniversary gift, which was very nice.

    Overall, I felt it was a bit overhyped, maybe not worth the 2 month wait, but regardless still a great restaurant to go to.

    My 3 courses started off with the glazed oysters with oestra caviar, zucchini pearls, and lettuce cream. Each mouthful left me wanting more and more. Next, I was greeted with seared sea scallops with sweet pea puree. Need I say more really? Scallops were perfectly cooked and the sweet pea puree elevated this mouthwatering seafood dish.
